^b@2^Y@3^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|This is the second of my 4 part lesson series on slam bidding, based on Marty Bergen's book ^*ISlam Bidding Made Easier^*N. Last week's lesson was on what is known as "Starting Points", how to evaluate your hand prior to the auction. This week's lesson is a continuation of last week's material. It is on Dummy Points and Declarer points, which is how to change your hand evaluation once you find a fit. |
PG| ***** 22 ***** |


cp|5|AT|
^b@2^Y@3^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Let me quickly review last week's lesson to set the stage for this week. Last week we talked about Starting Points, how to evaluate your hand prior to the auction. There were 5 rules we discussed.|
PG| ***** 23 ***** |


AT|

- The first was raw high card points, the usual Ace = 4, K = 3, Q = 2, and J = 1. |
PG| ***** 24 ***** |


AT|

- The second rule was suit length, 1 point for each card over 4 in a suit, hence 1 point for a 5 card suit, 2 points for a six card suit, etc. Those are the two most important.|
PG| ***** 25 ***** |


AT|

- The next rule was dubious singletons and doubletons. That is you subtract one point for each singleton K, Q, or J and one point for all doubletons containing a Q or J and not the Ace.|
PG| ***** 26 ***** |


AT|

- The 4th rule was quality suits. You add one point for each 4+ card suit with 3 of the top 5 honors, such as AK10x or QJ10xx. note that the 10 is considered an honor. |
PG| ***** 27 ***** |


AT|

- And the final rule is the most complicated, but fortunately it does not affect the hand evaluation much of the time. It has to do with the fact that the traditional 4-3-2-1 point count under values Aces and Tens, and, more importantly, over values Queens and Jacks (derisively called "|cp|5|at|quacks|cp||at|" by many experts). You count the number of Aces and Tens, and also the number of Queens and Jacks. If the number of Aces and Tens exceeds the quacks by 3 or more but less than six, you add a point. Conversely, if the number of quacks exceeds the Ace/Ten count by 3 or more but less than six, you subtract a point. Kings are valued exactly correctly at 3 points and they are not affected by this rule.|
PG| ***** 28 ***** |


