qx|A01, A - Adjusted HCP count|
HT|d|CS|4|AT|
^-{ A - Adjusted HCP count }
^-|
CP||fp|1|at|^B@2^Z@3L|fp||at|et us start with the first building block of Starting Points using the FORMULA |CS|4|AT|
^-
{               (A+L+Q) - D = SP               }
^-
|cp|5|FP|1|at|"A"|cp||FP||at| is upward adjustments for Aces and 10s and downward adjustments for Queens and Jacks, using the "Adjust 3" method. Bergen calls Aces and 10s under-valued and Queens and Jacks over-valued. He uses "Adjust-3" to bring the traditional HCP closer to its true value. 

Here, let me quote Howard as his explanation would make understanding this rather confusing subject very simple.|
PG| ***** 363 ***** |


AT|

"Although the traditional 4-3-2-1 method for counting high card points is simple and reasonably accurate, there are certain adjustments that can be made to increase its accuracy. In particular, Aces are undervalued, Queens and Jacks ("quacks") are over valued, and no value is placed on Tens. A more accurate point count system is:^-

{ A = 4.5, K = 3, Q = 1.5, J = .75, 10 = .25 }
^-|
PG| ***** 364 ***** |


AT|

"If you are mathematically inclined, you can count your high card points using the suggested fractions. However, most of us would find this rather complicated. So, there is a simplified method you can use. First, count the number of your ^*Iundervalued^*N honors (Aces and 10s). Then count the number of your ^*Iovervalued^*N honors (Queens and Jacks.)" |
PG| ***** 365 ***** |


AT|

"If the number of ^*Iovervalued^*N honors exceeds the number of ^*Iundervalued^*N honors by 3 or more but less than 6, then add 1 HCP to your hand (because your hand is worth more than simple HCP indicate.)"|
PG| ***** 366 ***** |


NT||
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
HT|d|CS|4|AT|
^-{ A - Adjusted HCP count }
^-|
CP||at|^B@2^Z@3"Similarly, if the number of ^*Iundervalued^*N honors exceeds the number of ^*Iovervalued^*N honors by 3 or more but less than 6, subtract 1 from your hand (because your hand is worth less than simple HCP indicate). For example, if you have five Aces and Tens, and two or less Queens and Jacks (quacks), you should add 1 to your HCP. Similarly, if you have 4 quacks and no more than 1 Ace or 10, you should subtract 1 from your HCP. Note that on rare occasions, the difference will be six or more (for example you have 6 quacks and no Aces or Tens). In that case you add or subtract 2 points either way. Marty Bergen terms this method (Adjust-3)."|
PG| ***** 367 ***** |


AT|

Now, for additional clarity let us repeat them.
|CS|4|AT|^-
{          Calculating "A" with Adjust-3          }
^-
^b1. Count the number of Aces and Tens.
^b2. Count the number of Queens and Jacks.
^b3. If the number of Aces and Tens exceeds the number of Queens and Jacks by 3 or more, add 1 to the number of HCP. In the rare instance where the number of Aces and Tens exceeds the number of Queens and Jacks by six or more, add 2 to the number of HCP.
^b4. Similarly, if the number of Queens and Jacks exceeds the number of Aces and Tens by 3 or more, subtract 1 to the number of HCP. In the rare instance where the number of Queens and Jacks exceeds the number of Aces and Tens by six or more, subtract 2 to the number of HCP.|
